LEISHMANIASIS - COLOMBIA (02): (NORTE DE SANTANDER) VISCERAL, ALERT
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 31 May 2017
Source: Caracol Radio [in Spanish, trans. Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ, edited]
http://caracol.com.co/emisora/2017/05/31/cucuta/1496227424_039580.html


An emergency situation is occurring in the village of Vetas, municipality of Tibú [Norte de Santander department] because of an outbreak of leishmaniasis, which has affected 56 people, including 10 Venezuelans and some pregnant women.

Maribel Trujillo, manager of the Tibú Hospital, said that so far no resources or a source of funding have been allocated for the treatment of Venezuelans who cross the border and reach this locality in the Catatumbo area. "The medical consultations that we are carrying out continue without any coverage and the situation is becoming more critical every day with the outbreak of leishmaniasis, which incudes 10 cases in Venezuelans and some pregnant women. In total for the outbreak, we already have 56 people affected, but we think there may be more Venezuelans in that group, since they are crossing the border looking for work."

The department's health authorities are conducting a review of the emergency in order to carry out a census in the rural area of the municipality.

