[Around 99 per cent of all leishmaniasis cases in Colombia are CL (cutaneous leishmaniasis); 0.4 per cent are MCL (mucocutaneous leishmaniasis), and 0.3 per cent are VL (visceral leishmaniasis). Leishmaniasis is especially common in sylvatic foci and in the inter-Andean valleys, where working on coffee plantations is a risk factor. Epidemic outbreaks of CL caused by _L. braziliensis_, _L. guyanensis_, and _L. panamensis_, have been reported since 1984. Urbanization of the disease has been observed in recent years (Alvat J et al: Leishmaniasis worldwide and global estimates of its incidence. PLoS One. 2012; 7(5): e35671. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0035671; http://journals.plos.org/plosone/doi?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0035671). - Mod.EP

Maps of Colombia can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/southamerica/map-of-Colmbia.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5079868,60927. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
